<font color="#FF0000">THANKS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 22 20:33:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This site has been an exercise of renewal, healing, and helping.  I would really like to thank all who were involved in giving we Viet Nam Vets a forum for all to see and interact with.  The unique thing that I found about this site was the various responses from all over the spectrum.  The spectrum being ages, philosphies, cultures and basic quests for knowledge and understanding.<br>
This was exciting to talk, complain, explain and remain to take the the slings and arrows of all those participating.  At no time was I ever able to feel that those discussions were not valuable and important to those of us seeking understanding.  In the process of learning about me and my time in Viet Nam I have personally dealt with a heavy load of B.S.  It was refreshing to talk with those who had &quot;been there, done that&quot;.  <br>
A lot of times it has been said that Viet Nam vets won't talk about their experience unless it is with someone who &quot;has been there&quot;. This is common because our feelings were discounted for so long that a belief was developed that only those who had been there could understand our behavior. This site has opened up a dialog between young people who really want to know what it was like, the educators who want to teach them what it was about, and even those who didn't agree with our gov'ts. policies. <br>
This site has become a place that I visit at least once a week.  It is a place that touches me as The Wall does.  If it didn't I think I would need to be back in counseling.  To read posts that bring tears and post replies that also bring tears is, believe it or not,  part of the healing process that so many of us need but have not accessed.  This is as close to a counseling center that many vets will ever get, mostly because of the anonimity.<br>
So, bottom line.  Thank you, PBS.  This is a wonderful thing that you have accomplished and I will miss it.<br>
Chet Botkins
